We acknowledge that trees, for example, have seasons; that for part of the year they are bare, silent, and unproductive, but we don’t easily recognize this natural system in our own timelines, in fact we fight off rest and recovery, resist downtime, hurry our healing. There was an expanse of time this year where too much hit the fan at once and old wounds I thought I had patched up unexpectedly split open, knocking me to my knees and bringing up wells of corrosive panic I hadn’t felt since I was a teenager. I couldn’t feel my self, couldn’t locate any inner depth I normally connect with. Getting back on track is taking a season, and a patience that has humbled my urgency to produce as if I am, alone, a factory. I am not, nor do I want to be. 

My Rider Muse girl existed before this year—you may have seen her on the T’s in my shop—but her purpose came back into focus for me this year. Now she’s a wearable pin. She is a reminder that come heaven or hell, I’m along for the ride. You are, too, aren’t ya? You’re good for the ups and downs, the peaks and valleys? Reminding myself of this simple commitment has helped restore my footing. If you believe it, there’s always energy at work within us, perfectly evolving forward—even when we’re at rest, even when we’re not “on,” maybe especially when we’re not “on.” And when you intentionally rely on it—on yourself—it’s suddenly just a little breezier to ride through all the seasons, however they come. 
——

Embrace your snakes. Hold them close. Offer a resonance so welcoming that they can do no harm. When we befriend our fears, the enemy, or even our own antagonistic thinking, we shift from resistance to freedom—what used to signal danger now signals an opportunity for a deeper understanding of our own minds. Serpents have long been dualistic symbols of good and evil. Here, entwined with the welcoming female form, the dangerous serpent becomes rather a protector and guide.

Wear the Serpentine Scarf as apparel, or hang it as wall art.

LIMITED SUPPLY BEFORE HOLIDAYS, SHIPS IMMEDIATELY!

Vocab of the day: IRREPLICABLE. Ain’t nothing soulful or nutritious about “artificial.” The masses will buy hot shit off the sidewalk, that’s all this AI trend tells me and I didn’t need the reminder. I’m always hungry for Actual Intelligence. Real life play, creativity, skill, execution. What a turn on. There’s an age old, very magical, irrepliclable communication that occurs between artist and subject, and it can’t be mechanized for $3.99. If you’ve never sat for a drawing or painting, I suggest you do it in once in this lifetime. I’ve been offering body portraits for years. All my favorite artists offer interpretive portraits. You’ll get an experience of human capacity versus a little hit of Narcissus-brand crack that makes you momentarily fall in love with your own reflection in a fake pool of water. Not to mention all the theft happening from actual creatives. Pass! I’m always aiming my trajectory away from virtual toward more and more traditional—the earthen dirt of life and whatever it grows.

Throughout adolescence, my sketchbooks were filled with superheroines, tank girls, girls with guns…women in their power. Later, my sense of power became subtler, I developed an aesthetic style that emphasizes and exaggerates what I find strong and beautiful instead. But still, I like the symbolism of a weapon-wielding woman. If it’s in her hands, there’s something sacred to be protected, it’s not likely a power trip or means of control. I always say, if y’all won’t protect us, we’ll protect ourselves. Here’s a few gals looking damn cute doing it.

They name my kind as having a “bittersweet condition”…a near-constant melancholy that nevertheless brings with it awe, wonder, and contentment in finding depth. Some days it is not easy for me to be awake—no matter where I go, and how much beauty and love I absorb, my safest place remains drawing, alone. But I love every moment I have and aim only to increasingly welcome the entire range of the heartbreakingly beautiful experiences we get, deeply and profoundly, all of it. When I am old and grey, you can come visit me on the mountain of quiet joy I will have built by then.

BYE! I’ve deleted 13 years of posts. Increasingly, my art “goes against community guidelines,” and I won’t keep feeding a machine that’s trying to eat me. After much thought, I realize that what I ✨MOST LOVE✨ and find ⚡️⚡️ MOST SACRED ⚡️⚡️ may not belong to the public anymore, and that my work is not created to be absorbed flippantly between jokes and the day’s bad news. It’s become so noisy here. 

I’m not one to sit in misalignment long; I tend to seek revelation, repair, and growth in the spaces and relationships I occupy. So I’m not abandoning ship; I’m going to resacralize this space between us and find more protected and intimate ways of sharing my work, and DIRECTLY connecting with ✨YOU✨ if you want to engage with ME. I used to reach 250,000 people per week organically with my posts. That was then, this is now, there are no masterpieces, nothing to cling to, only what we do next. IG and FB—as they’ve become—are over for me. 👋🏽💋 I’m excited to come up with new ways of crafting more meaningful connections as our personal and collective needs are changing. 

I’m starting by inviting you to a livestream screening of a 3-min short film I’ve just finished. It’s about something I’ve NEVER shared previously, that shaped my identity and career in both the childrens’ books and my figurative art. I want to unveil it to a smaller group of people who can comment and ask questions live. 
JOIN ME FOR A LIVESTREAM SCREENING + Q&A:
Bound: Bones + Bodies | A short film 
Wed May 10th 
7:00 – 7:30 pm PT/10:00–10:30pm ET
REGISTER VIA LINK IN BIO

Thanks for riding along with me.
🖤🤘🏽

BOUND: BONES + BODIES | A short film about Los Angeles artist and author-illustrator Ruby Roth and a personal experience that shaped her identity and career in figurative art and children’s books. From first-of-their-kind picture books to evocative figure drawings and paintings, Ruby weaves together  a world of seemingly divergent bodies of work. But in the context of her origins story, the through-line becomes clear—paralleling her own journeys, Roth’s women, children, and animals are all finding their way through the splendors and travails of the earth, always seeking a sacred balance. 

———

Last year I wanted to be in a new state physically and mentally when hit 40 on June 27, 2022. I got what I asked for, just not in the way I had imagined. I was knocked to my knees, suddenly looping daily in an old state of panic so intense that I dropped to 74 pounds, enrolled myself in an intensive outpatient program with 2x/week ketamine for 8 weeks, and stayed asleep as much as I could, fearing consciousness. If someone had told me it would take a year to begin to heal I don’t know if I would have survived the thought. I wasn’t suicidal, I just didn’t want to be here on Earth. But now a year doesn’t seem like much time at all to devote to changing patterns and neural pathways, especially those we’ve been reinforcing since childhood.

This 40-41 was a year of reconciliation—with death, how I absorb the dark side of reality, with the consequences of being boundaryless, and with the abyss we all face at one time or another. I thought I had a pretty solid spiritual life and a collected well of wisdom I pulled strength from. While that was true, I’ve been humbled to learn that there were parts of me that don’t know a thing about how to live. A piece of me understood that if you can’t connect to awe and a certain amount of joy or peace, there is something you don’t yet know about living. Holy shit, we are all students. I do not seek joy, but I do seek the mastery of my mind and consciousness. On the worst days, a shred of self understood my assignment. I am still healing, but I can kinda laugh now that I’ll be recovering from turning 40-41 for the next decade. 

Anything I accomplished this past year was done by sheer will, on days I could, and with the help of my family and friends, and both western and alternative medicine and therapies. Thank you all for following along, even when I went radio silent for awhile. The art you see is just one manifestation of the art of living I am sharpening my ways with. One day, I hope to be a wise old woman making art on a peaceful mountain, and you can visit me there. 

Love,
Ruby 
#41

I’m REALLY f*cking excited about this one in progress and I felt like telling you rn. And also this—I’ve got a certain set of standards when it comes to painting. I honor the craft so much, and so deeply respect how far just a relatively few select humans have been able to take it, that it will probably be years before I call myself a “painter.” And this makes me a bitch to to go art shows with because while I 100% enjoy, love, and am supportive of, a broad range of art and artists, I can’t help it— it’s always clear AF who’s functioning on schtick, who’s made their art out of copying photos (which, don’t be fooled, is not that hard), who should be called a “cleverist,” not an artist, and who, rather exhibits—or is even just crafting a relationship with—a deep understanding of their mediums and line, form, light, color, saturation, hue, value, composition, shape, edges, tangents, unique style, etc., not to mention the ability to capture and illicit emotion. That’s all, I love all kinds of art, I’m just saying I love the craft of drawing and painting SO much and it is a HARD, LIFELONG, BILLIONS-OF-HOURS journey to become what, in IMHO, is a “great” artist, and I’ll always place a higher value on that than becoming a commercial “success, and I’ll never stop learning. Or hating on cheaters and corner-cutters, LOL.

I love when you all go to sleep safe and sound, and my midnights belong to quiet cultivation. It’s never lost on me that I get to basically fingerpaint like a kindergartener at night while others suffer hell on Earth. All I have to say is I do my best to keep my footprint here light and spread light where I recognize darkness, trying never to look away from where attention is needed—and darkness is always tugging at me. I was born the “bittersweet” kind— humanity mostly saddens me more than amazes me. But I find meaning and depth and great love in digging for the good, everywhere and in everyone. Thinking on peace and sending you all love. 🖤

Here’s one trueass truth I’ve learned and keep learning: the process of “becoming” can be, plain and simply, ugly. With paint, in relationships, in career, in psychological or spiritual betterment, in reaching sobriety, in healing, maybe even human evolution. If you don’t recognize that, you’ll sit miserable and anxious in the ugliness. You might throw the towel in too soon. But if you acknowledge the peaks and valleys that evolving requires, say “Oh I know what this is,” and discipline yourself into the patience to hold space for what comes next, you’ll often land on a refined result that you can be content with. Basically, be prepared for what it looks like to level up—it ain’t always a pretty process.

Being in problem-solving mode is an archetypically masculine state on the spectrum. It took me many years to notice that my life force/energy starts degrading in a matter of weeks when, for whatever reason, I’ve had to shore up my masculine side, day in and day out, in a prolonged loop. It’s easy to do when you’re good at thinking, good in a crisis, good at work, good at stepping up to bat. But for people with feminine cores, it soon feels like being pulled out of alignment and then all body/mind/spirit systems start going awry. People with masculine cores also need a feminine balance to thrive. 

I know a lot of people are hurting right now, along with world news, or by overproducing, underproducing, can’t sleep, can’t eat, energy dwindling, etc. One of the last #inktober prompts, which I missed, was “MASSIVE.” This is the image that came to my mind, a girl god channeling massive energy, hands open to the feminine state of RECEIVING. We can’t always DO/SOLVE/ACT our way out of problems, sometimes the key is simply, at least for a few moments, to shift our mode of being into RECEIVING for answers. A reminder to anyone feeling awry—try tapping into the feminine as a manner of rebalancing. 🖤

NEW BOOK⚡️“BOSS INSIDE: A RECLAMATION OF THE FEMININE” is a revealing collection of artist Ruby Roth’s deeply private journal entries, artwork, and photographs 2016 to 2020 as she left a 14-year identity-defining relationship that had shaped her entire adulthood. The shift was a personal apocalypse and required a radical turn in focus, from matrimonial dependence to self-determined autonomy. BOSS INSIDE chronicles the evolution and disintegration of a profoundly influential first love and Roth’s fierce, sacred, and often broiling path toward the reclamation of her creativity, her femininity, and sexuality, as she navigates jelling independence, a diverging career, and new relationships to men and masculinity itself. Free will makes her body a new home, the locus through which she begins drawing subject matter and a redefinition of self as she depicts a manifested relationship with a “cowboy from Texas,” an introduction to rage, her brutal realizations of loss, and the healing processes that ushered her along, determined to let everything she felt be the muse of transformation.

“Cycles of life forces and death forces,” she writes, “and us, the vessels.”

The thought of that stretch felt like death at the time. But now a year+ doesn’t seem like very long when it comes to healing, making change, or implementing a grand shift. It takes tiiiiiiiime, dedicated time. I don’t live by horoscopes, but I’ve sure kept my eye on the fucking calendar LOL. Hope whatever heaviness y’all have been through this year lifts in 2024, too. Thank you for watching me walk myself into a new chapter with #BossInside and the rest.

The last drawing in my book, BOSS INSIDE. It’s a symbol of surrender at the end of a journey—the bent flowers, crunched toes pressed upon the earth, a peaceful pose but subtly hardened expression. Her body is gently caved, but she leans on herself, held up by her own strength and the solid ground beneath her. Planned to be the last image readers take in, this drawing is about the injuries we sustain and the beauty and life force that still remains intact.
